{{short description|Proposed aircraft to fill the middle of the market segment}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}
[[File:N535US (12274798093).jpg|thumb|The New Midsize Airplane would have been sized between the [[Boeing 757|757]] (front) and [[Boeing 767|767]] (rear) in the [[middle of the market]].]]

The '''New Midsize Airplane''' ('''NMA'''), or '''New Midsize Aircraft''',<ref name="Emirates NMA" /> is a concept [[airliner]] proposed by [[Boeing]] to fill the [[middle of the market]] segment.

In 2015, Boeing determined the market was large enough to launch a new design. In 2017, multiple airlines expressed interest in a composite, seven-abreast [[twin-aisle]] with an elliptical cross-section. The new aircraft, which would likely have been named the '''Boeing 797''',<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bennett |first=Jay |date=2017-06-23 |title=Boeing 797? Aviation Giant Teases New Airliner at Paris Air Show |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/flight/airlines/news/a27055/797-boeing-nma-new-airliner/ |access-date=2021-04-06 |website=Popular Mechanics|language=en-US}}</ref><!--<ref name=ST170308/>--> would be available in two versions: a 225-seater with {{cvt|5000|nmi|km}} [[range (aeronautics)|range]] and a 275-seater with a range of {{cvt|4500|nmi|km}}.<!--<ref name=aw20180207/>--> Third-party forecasts for this market varied from 2,000 to 4,000 aircraft, though Boeing expected the market demand to lie at the upper end of this range.<!--<ref name=leeham20180213/>--> At a projected price of $65–75 million, the NMA was expected to generate 30% more revenue than [[narrowbody|narrowbodies]] and have 40% lower [[trip cost]]s than the widebodies it would have replaced.<!--<ref name=leeham20180305/>--> <!--engines-->It would have been powered by a new {{cvt|50,000|lbf|kN}} turbofan from [[GE Aviation]]/[[CFM International]] or [[Pratt & Whitney]], with a [[bypass ratio]] of 10:1 or more and an [[overall pressure ratio]] exceeding 50:1.

In January 2020, Boeing put the plans on hold and announced a clean-sheet reevaluation of the project, noting that it was focused on returning the [[737 MAX]] to service and would be taking a new approach to future projects.<!--ref name=Reuters23jan2020--> By February 2021, the company appeared to have revived the project with plans for a shorter variant that could enter service by the late 2020s with a development cost of up to $25 billion.<!--ref name=AvWeek4feb2021--> In June 2022, however, it announced that the development would not be pursued until new engines and development tools are mature.<!--ref name=seattletimes20220603-->

== History ==

=== 2015 ===
At Air Lease Corp. [[Steven F. Udvar-Házy]] believed that Boeing was planning to launch a more capable, all-new replacement for the [[Boeing 757]] rather than a re-engined version.<ref>{{cite news |author= Laura Mueller |url= http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/alc-sees-757-being-replaced-rather-than-re-engined-409553/ |title= ALC sees 757 being replaced rather than re-engined |work=[[Flightglobal]]|date= February 27, 2015}}</ref> At the [[International Society of Transport Aircraft Trading]] conference, he predicted it would be a [[Boeing 767]]-like, twin-aisle airplane capable of using {{convert|7000|ft|sigfig=3|adj=on}} runways such as those at [[New York LaGuardia]]. Boeing's VP of Marketing Randy Tinseth said the company focused on developing an aircraft with 20% more range and capacity than the 757-200.<ref>{{cite news |author= Stephen Trimble |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/udvar-hazy-reveals-preferences-for-boeing39s-next-409999/ |title= Udvar-Hazy reveals preferences for Boeing's next project |work= Flight Global |date= March 11, 2015}}</ref> [[United Airlines]] consulted Airbus and Boeing about replacing its 757s and was waiting for Boeing's response, as Tinseth wanted to fill the gap between the [[Boeing 737 MAX|737 MAX]] and the [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|787]].<ref name=ain2015-03-11>{{cite news |author= Gregory Polek |url= http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/air-transport/2015-03-11/united-studying-replacements-its-transatlantic-757s |title= United Studying Replacements for Its Transatlantic 757s |work= Aviation International News |date= March 11, 2015}}</ref>

Before the 2015 [[Paris Air Show]], sales chief John Wojick said Boeing had held discussions with customers and determined that the market was large enough to launch an all-new [[jet airliner]], the first since the launch of the 787 Dreamliner in 2003.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-looking-closely-at-an-all-new-jet-for-2025/ |title= Boeing looking closely at an all-new jet for 2025 |date= June 14, 2015 |work= The Seattle Times |author= Dominic Gates |author-link=Dominic Gates}}</ref> At the show, Airbus CEO [[Fabrice Bregier]] estimated that Boeing would have to invest $10 billion to develop a 757 successor with 220 seats and a range of {{cvt|4500|nmi|km}}, corresponding to the capabilities stated by Boeing's vice president for product development Mike Sinnett.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-17/boeing-jet-that-doesn-t-exist-yet-becomes-talk-of-paris-air-show |title= Paris Air Show Buzzes Over Boeing Jet That Doesn't Exist Yet |work= Bloomberg |date= 17 June 2015}}</ref> Vinay Bhaskara of [[Airways News]] said Boeing's ''middle of the market'' (MOM) airliner would likely launch before 2020 and enter service in the early part of the following decade.<ref name=AN150618>{{cite news |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/boeings-mystery-plane-has-the-paris-air-show-buzzing-2015-6 |title= Boeing's mystery plane is the big story coming out of the Paris Air Show |work= Business Insider |date= 18 June 2015}}</ref>

Boeing denied that the new aircraft would be an update to the Boeing 767,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://leehamnews.com/2015/08/19/boeing-sees-healthy-future-for-767/ |title= Boeing sees "healthy" future for 767 |date= 19 August 2015 |work= Leeham News}}</ref> although a revised 767 could be a possible stopgap measure.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2015/08/27/boeings-767-revitalized-as-a-mom-stop-gap/ |title= Boeing's 767 revitalized as a MOM stop gap? |author= Bjorn Fehrm |date= August 27, 2015 |work= Leeham News}}</ref> Estimates suggested that developing and building a new aircraft could reach US$15 billion.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.aspireaviation.com/2015/09/24/the-search-for-boeing-mom/ |title= The search for Boeing's MOM |date= September 24, 2015 |work= Aspire Aviation}}</ref>

=== 2016 ===
[[File:N27752 Boeing 737-MAX 10 demonstrator STN 081222 (52551773020).jpg|thumb|The [[Boeing 737 MAX|737 MAX 10]] remained the largest and heaviest [[Boeing 737]] variant ever and is likely ended up the ultimate development of its family. Yet to be certified to enter commercial service as of 2025, the MAX 10 still has considerable operating range disadvantage comparing to its direct competitor [[Airbus A321neo]], especially with the A321LR and A321XLR.]]

In early 2016, Boeing's two major options remained a larger 737 MAX variant or an all-new 797 design.<ref name=ST160302>{{Cite news |url= http://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-wrestles-with-options-for-new-mid-sized-jet/ |title= Boeing wrestles with options for new midsize jet |date= March 2, 2016 |work= The Seattle Times |author= Dominic Gates}}</ref> The MOM was the subject of a session of the 2016 International Society of Transport Aircraft Trading (ISTAT) conference in [[Phoenix, Arizona]] where major worldwide sellers, buyers and financiers of commercial aircraft meet.<ref name=ST160302/> [[Airbus]] sales chief [[John Leahy (executive)|John Leahy]] said the industry has no need for a new midmarket airplane, since the [[Airbus A321neo]] is already for sale.<ref name=ST160302/>

In July 2016, Boeing forecast demand for 4,000 to 5,000 midmarket aircraft, leaving a market for 2,000 to 3,000 after accounting for the Airbus A321neo and [[Airbus A330neo|A330neo]] sales.<ref name=V1ewpoint17Q2/> It identified the market "sweet spot" for the NMA as being a 200 to 250-seat twin-aisle aircraft with more than {{cvt|4000|nmi|km}} range, but less expensive to operate than existing small twin aisles. The notional aircraft, which would enter service in the middle of the next decade, would need advanced {{convert|40,000|-|45,000|lbf|kN|abbr=on}} [[high-bypass turbofan]]s with higher pressure ratios.<!--<ref name=AW170220 />--> Boeing development resources were committed on the [[Boeing 777X|777X]], [[Boeing 787-10|787-10]] and 737 MAX, whereas Airbus's R&D spending profile appeared to leave room for new development, but Airbus believed that the [[Airbus A321LR|A321LR]] and A330neo were sufficient to address the segment.<ref name=AW170220>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-considers-next-midmarket-moves-airbus-watches |title= Boeing Considers Next Midmarket Moves As Airbus Watches |date= February 20, 2017 |author= Guy Norris and Jens Flottau |work=[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]]}}</ref>

=== 2017 ===
At the March 2017 ISTAT Americas conference, United Airlines' interest in the NMA was confirmed by chief financial officer Andrew Levy, who corroborated the assumption that it would be a [[twin-aisle]] aircraft<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/united-very-interested-in-boeing-mom-concept-434905/ |title= United 'very interested' in Boeing MoM concept |date= 7 March 2017 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> with two variants, carrying 225 to 260 passengers with a range of {{cvt|4,800|to|5,200|nmi|km}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-airline-support-gathers-around-boeing-mom-434961/ |title= Airline support gathers around Boeing MoM concept |date= March 9, 2017 |work= Flight Global |author= Edward Russell}}</ref> Multiple airlines expressed potential interest: [[Alaska Airlines]],<ref name=ST170308/> [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]],<ref name="Emirates NMA">{{Cite web |url= http://aviationweek.com/awincommercial/emirates-considers-boeing-s-midsize-aircraft-winner |title= Emirates Considers Boeing's Midsize Aircraft 'A Winner' |author= Jens Flottau |work= Aviation Daily |publisher= Aviation Week |date= March 9, 2017 |url-access= subscription}}</ref> and [[Delta Air Lines]] for [[transatlantic flight]]s.<ref name=ST170308>{{Cite news |url= http://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-talking-with-airlines-about-a-797-and-they-like-what-they-hear/ |title= Boeing's talking with airlines about a '797,' and they like what they hear |date= March 8, 2017 |work= The Seattle Times |author= Dominic Gates}}</ref>

The new airplane was expected to have seven-abreast seating, like the 767.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/new-midsize-airplane-will-define-boeings-technology-roadmap |title= New Midsize Airplane Will Define Boeing's Technology Roadmap |date= March 17, 2017 |author= Jens Flottau |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> The market favors [[single-aisle]] economics, and Boeing's challenge would be to achieve comparable hourly cost and price per seat while keeping [[twin-aisle]] capabilities.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/opinion-boeing-s-twin-aisle-midsize-jet-faces-big-challenges |title= Opinion: Boeing's Twin-Aisle Midsize Jet Faces Big Challenges |date= March 28, 2017 |author= Richard Aboulafia |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> Competition to supply the engines would be intense, with Rolls-Royce expected to propose the UltraFan follow-on to its [[Rolls-Royce Trent#Research|Advance]] engines, Pratt & Whitney offering a new iteration of its [[Pratt & Whitney Geared Turbofan]], and [[CFM International]] also in the running.<ref name=AW170406>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/rolls-royce-might-pitch-ultrafan-boeing-new-midsize-airplane |title= Rolls-Royce Might Pitch UltraFan For Boeing New Midsize Airplane |date= April 3, 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>

To assess where the "middle of the market" lay, Flight Ascend Consultancy looked at existing twin-aisle aircraft with fewer than 260 seats and found that these offered an average of 234 seats and have an average flight distance of 2,670&nbsp;nmi, with 60% of [[available seat miles]] below 4,000&nbsp;nmi and 82% below 5,000&nbsp;nmi.<ref name=V1ewpoint17Q2/> To be competitive, NMA pricing would have to be between the 787-8 and A330neo at $100–120 million (base full-life value) and larger single-aisles at above $50 million; the 767-300ER in its heyday cost just over $70 million.<ref name=V1ewpoint17Q2>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/asset/16524 |title= Where is the middle of the market? |author= Chris Seymour |pages=12–15 |work= V1ewpoint |date= Spring 2017 |issue= 55 |publisher= Flight Ascend Consultancy}}</ref> An [[Ellipse|elliptical]] cross-section could combine a twin-aisle cabin with the reduced cargo space of a single-aisle jet to reduce [[aerodynamic drag]] and operating costs, but would need more complex [[carbon composite]]s instead of a simple cylindrical metal [[fuselage]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-airlines-iata-boeing-idUSKBN18Y2TW |date= June 7, 2017 |title= Boeing studies 'mild to wild' design for pivotal mid-market jet |author= Tim Hepher |work= Reuters}}</ref>

Boeing relies on [[model-based systems engineering]] (MBSE), already used in its defense and space businesses, to define [[customer]] needs and functionality early in the [[aircraft design process]] with an [[interdisciplinary]] approach.<!--<ref name=AvWeek12Jun2017/>--> A [[systems architecture]] model feeds and interacts with [[Analysis|analytic]] and [[Verification and validation|verification]] models, and helps define the product to bound [[data management]] and control cost and schedule, and the constraints, interfaces and requirements.<!--<ref name=AvWeek12Jun2017/>--> Engine integration defines [[takeoff]] and [[Climb (aeronautics)|climb]] capability, [[aircraft noise]] and [[ETOPS]] range circumference and engine failure altitude.<ref name=AvWeek12Jun2017>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-unveil-first-new-midsize-airplane-details-paris |title= Boeing To Unveil First New Midsize Airplane Details In Paris |date= June 12, 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>

[[File:Boeing New Midsize Airplane side view.jpeg|thumb|Silhouettes of Boeing NMA concept at right between 787-8 on top and 737 MAX 10 on bottom, as presented at Paris Air Show 2017]]
At the June 2017 Paris Air Show, Boeing's aircraft development manager Mike Delaney confirmed the use of composites for the whole [[airframe]], which would have a hybrid cross-section and [[bypass ratio]]s above 10:1.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-boeing-partially-unveils-new-midsize-airplan-438512/ |author= Stephen Trimble |work= Flightglobal |title= Boeing partially unveils New Midsize Airplane concept |date= 20 June 2017}}</ref> If the NMA were to be launched in early 2019, its design would be completed in 2020, with fabrication in 2021–22, build in 2023, flight tests and certification in 2024 and introduction in 2025.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/paris-air-show-2017/boeing-outlines-notional-nma-timetable |title= Boeing Outlines Notional NMA Timetable |date= June 20, 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work=Aviation Week Network}}</ref>

With the NMA planned for introduction no earlier than 2025, and the 787 being much larger, Boeing could conceivably restart passenger 767-300ER production to bridge the gap,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2017/08/14/boeings-tactical-option-for-mom-sector/ |title= Boeing's tactical option for MOM sector |date= August 14, 2017 |work= Leeham}}</ref> with potential demand for 50 to 60 aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2017/10/19/boeing-ponders-restart-767-300er-passenger-line/ |title= Boeing ponders restart of 767-300ER passenger line |date= October 19, 2017 |work= Leeham}}</ref> In September, Boeing created a development program office, and in November named their company veteran and 777X chief project engineer Terry Beezhold, without a role yet.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://money.cnn.com/2017/11/20/news/companies/boeing-797-nma-chief-engineer/index.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171121011208/http://money.cnn.com/2017/11/20/news/companies/boeing-797-nma-chief-engineer/index.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= November 21, 2017 |title= Boeing's '797' takes a big step toward becoming reality |author= Jon Ostrower |date= November 20, 2017 |work= CNN}}</ref> Its introduction could slip from 2024–25 to 2027, pushing the 737 replacement to after 2030.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2017/12/04/boeing-moves-eis-target-nma-2027-sources/ |title= Boeing moves EIS target for NMA to 2027: sources |date= December 4, 2017 |work= Leeham}}</ref>

On 20 December 2017, Washington Governor [[Jay Inslee]] formed a committee with Boeing labor unions ([[International Association of Machinists]] (IAM) and [[Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace]] (SPEEA)) and local government economic-development officials to lobby Boeing to build the NMA in [[Washington state]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/government-labor-and-industry-groups-join-to-lobby-boeing-on-building-next-plane-here |title= Government, labor, industry groups join to lobby Boeing on building next plane in Washington state |date= December 20, 2017 |author= Dominic Gates |work= Seattle Times}}</ref> Boeing continued to estimate middle-of-the-market demand at between 2,000 and 4,000 airliners over 20 years, stating in September 2017 that it was closer to 4,000, while [[Pratt & Whitney]], [[Rolls-Royce plc]] and Leeham Co. think it likely to lie between 2,000 and 2,500; Airbus puts the figure at about 2,000 aircraft, not enough to justify a new $15bn development program for aircraft to be sold for $55m to $75m each.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/01/03/nma-market-sector-small-airbus-leahy-says/ |title= NMA market sector is small, Airbus' Leahy says |date= Jan 3, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref>

=== 2018 ===
[[File:Boeing-NMA-2018-rendering.png|thumb|2018 early design rendering]]

In early 2018, United saw the NMA reach the market in eight to ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/aviation-finance-united/united-sees-potential-new-boeing-jet-available-in-8-10-years-idUSS8N1O3024 |date= Jan 23, 2018 |title= United sees potential new Boeing jet available in 8-10 years |work= Reuters}}</ref> GE Aviation expected a launch decision in 2018 in order to enter service on target in the mid-2020s.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/singapore-ge-expects-boeing-nma-decision-this-year-445563/ |title= GE expects Boeing NMA decision this year |date= 6 Feb 2018 |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> Boeing was in "active" talks with about 50 potential customers and had defined two main versions: a 225-seat model with a {{cvt|5,000|nmi|km}} range and a 275-seat version with a {{cvt|4,500|nmi|km}} range.<ref name=aw20180207>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-still-lot-be-decided-nma |title= Boeing: Still 'A Lot' To Be Decided On NMA |date= Feb 7, 2018 |author= Michael Bruno |work= Aviation Week Network}}</ref>

<!--market-->
Delta Air Lines hoped to be a launch customer for the NMA, which would replace its 757 and 767 fleets.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-13/delta-ceo-eyes-launch-customer-status-as-boeing-mulls-797-jet |title= Delta's Boss Wants to Be a Launch Customer on Boeing's '797' Jet |author= Michael Sasso |date= 13 Feb 2018 |agency= Bloomberg}}</ref> In February 2018, Delta operated {{#expr:111+16}} 757s and {{#expr:59+21}} 767s with average ages of 15 to 22 years.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-interested-in-boeing-nma-to-replace-757-and-76-445886/ |title= Delta interested in Boeing NMA to replace 757 and 767s |date= 13 Feb 2018 |author= Edward Russell |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> Boeing's VP Marketing Randy Tinseth was confident its [[forecasting|forecast]] of 4,000 aircraft can be met, despite others seeing the market as between 2,000 and 2,500, because the NMA would be able to change [[airline]] networks in the same way that the 787 enabled 170 new routes to be opened since 2011.<ref name=leeham20180213>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/02/13/nma-demand-skeptics-arent-thinking-outside-box-boeing-exec-says/ |title= NMA demand skeptics aren't thinking outside the box, Boeing exec says |date= Feb 13, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref> Solid production costs and sales forecasts would be required to convince the Boeing board to commit to its development.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-nma-decision-time-looms-for-boeing-445952/ |title= NMA decision time looms for Boeing |date= 16 Feb 2018 |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> [[Avolon]] saw a market for 3,500 to 4,000 airliners.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-06/boeing-faces-u-s-asia-cargo-clash-in-design-of-new-797-jet |title= Boeing Faces Airline Tug of War Over Proposed '797' Jet Design |date= 6 March 2018 |first= Julie |last= Johnson |agency= Bloomberg}}</ref> At the 2018 Farnborough Airshow, GE Aviation expressed concern as to whether the size of the market was large enough to justify the investment of developing a new engine for the jet.<ref>{{cite news |title=General Electric unconvinced about demand for Boeing's new 797 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/transport-and-tourism/general-electric-unconvinced-about-demand-for-boeing-s-new-797-1.3567152 |access-date=26 January 2020 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=16 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

<!--economics-->
The NMA was targeted to achieve a 30% economic improvement over the Boeing 757/767.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/02/12/pontifications-nma-boeing-embraer-headline-singapore-air-show/ |title= Pontifications: NMA, Boeing-Embraer headline Singapore Air Show |first= Scott |last= Hamilton |date= Feb 12, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref> Tinseth said the NMA would generate 30% more revenue than narrowbodies and have 40% lower [[trip cost]]s compared to the widebodies it would replace (767, A300 and A330).<ref name=leeham20180305>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/03/05/engine-makers-inside-tent-boeing-nma-airframer-still-ponders-provider/ |title= Engine makers "inside the tent" on Boeing NMA, but airframer still ponders provider |date= March 5, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref> Within its range, it would be significantly more economical than the A330neo, severely testing its sales if Boeing could keep NMA prices in the $70m range.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/03/06/retirement-wave-coming-will-boost-a330neo-sales-says-airbus/ |title= Retirement wave coming that will boost A330neo sales, says Airbus |date= March 6, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref> The target sale price for the NMA was believed to be between $65m and $75m.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/03/20/production-transformation-key-to-boeing-nma/ |title= Production transformation key to Boeing NMA |date= March 20, 2018 |work= Leeham}}</ref> [[Ryanair]] CEO [[Michael O'Leary (Ryanair)|Michael O'Leary]], kept informed by Boeing, said its [[seat cost]] would be substantially higher than the 737 MAX.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.luchtvaartnieuws.nl/nieuws/categorie/2/airlines/ryanair-ceo-boeing-797-niet-efficient-genoeg |title= Ryanair CEO: Boeing 797 niet efficient genoeg |date= 6 March 2018 |work= Luchtvaartnieuws |language= nl}}</ref>

<!--design-->
The conceptual design released in early 2018 had a 737 MAX-style tail cone, large 787/777X-sized cabin windows, a 757/767/777-style windscreen, a 767-200 door arrangement and short engine inlets.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://jonostrower.com/2018/03/the-boeing-797-of-2025-is-this-2018-conceptual-nma-rendering/ |title= This is Boeing's NMA |date= 12 March 2018 |author= Jon Ostrower}}</ref> As the A320/A330 investment has been [[Amortization (accounting)|amortized]], the A321LR or A330neo could be offered at a lower cost; the NMA would have to offer notably lower fuel and maintenance cost.<!--<ref name= Flight20mar2018>--> Airbus could react with an A321 stretch or an all-new design, and could use a new 50,000&nbsp;lbf (222.5&nbsp;kN) engine.<ref name= Flight20mar2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-how-boeings-nma-could-shake-up-the-market-446818/ |title= How Boeing's NMA could shake up the market |date= 20 March 2018 |first= Max |last= Kingsley-Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>

<!--timeframe-->
As recent all-new designs took between 88 and 101 months ({{#expr:88/12round1}} to {{#expr:101/12round1}} years) between the authority to offer and the introduction, late 2018 to early 2019 launch would have implied a 2026 service entry.<!--<ref name= Flight16may2018>--> At this time, existing airliners over 30 years old will have been replaced by current models, leaving 900 aircraft aged from 15 to 25 years to be replaced: 420 A321s, 270 A330-200s, 90 757s and 130 767s.<!--<ref name= Flight16may2018>--> The largest operator of these 15-to-25-year-old mid-market types is [[American Airlines]] with over 80, followed by [[China Southern]] then [[Delta Air Lines]], [[United Airlines]], [[Air China]] and [[Turkish Airlines]] with less than 40.<ref name=Flight16may2018>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-boeing-nma-when-and-who-will-order-448642/ |title= Boeing NMA – when, and who will order? |date= 16 May 2018 |first= Richard |last= Evans |work= Flight global}}</ref> In June the NMA-6X was defined as a 228-passenger, {{cvt |5,000|nmi|km}} airliner and the NMA-7X would seat 267 in two classes over {{cvt |4200|nmi|km}}.<ref name= Ostrower26jun2018 />

<!--market size-->
[[ICF International]] saw a market of 3,000–3,500 over 20 years with the NMA sold for $75–80 m, while [[Collateral Verifications]] believed in a 1,000–1,500 market and an $80–90 m price; for [[Flightglobal]]'s Ascend, 1,500 NMAs could have been delivered for $67–82 m each between 2025 and 2040 if its size was right, and [[Oriel Consult]] expected a $70–80 m price.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/09/11/disagreements-on-nma-market-footprint/ |title= Disagreements on NMA market footprint |date= Sep 11, 2018 |author= Airfinance Journal |work= Leeham News}}</ref> For Steven F. Udvar-Házy, a decision should be made by mid 2019, with two potential engines derived from existing units.<!--<ref name=Leeham13sep2018>--> Boeing continued to assess the market as 4,000-5,000 aircraft and was working towards a 2019 decision too, while taking measures to protect a 2025 introduction into service.<ref name=Leeham13sep2018>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/09/13/hazy-expects-797-decision-middle-next-year/ |title= Hazy expects 797 decision middle next year |date= Sep 13, 2018 |author= Airfinance Journal |work= Leeham News}}</ref>

<!--cross-section-->
[[File:MIT and Aurora D8 wide body passenger aircraft concept 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|The [[Aurora D8]] concept has a double bubble fuselage.]]

According to the French National Aerospace Research Center, [[ONERA]], a cylindrical seven or eight-abreast twin-aisle has 20% more fuselage drag in cruise than a six-abreast, single-aisle airplane of the same seat capacity. This is significant because fuselage drag is one-third of total drag.<!--<ref name=AvWeek19sep2018>--> However, an elliptical widebody can have an equivalent drag due to a smaller [[Skin friction drag|wetted area]]. Also, a twin-aisle is more comfortable and has faster [[Aircraft ground handling|turnaround]]s than a single-aisle.<!--<ref name=AvWeek19sep2018>--> A cylindrical section is the simplest way to cope with the [[cabin pressurization]]'s [[hoop stress]] while an elliptical section is reinforced and heavier (less so with vertical rods like the [[Aurora D8]] concept).<ref name=AvWeek19sep2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/new-civil-aircraft/boeing-nma-engine-and-fuselage-shape-selections-loom |title= Boeing NMA Engine And Fuselage-Shape Selections Loom |date= Sep 19, 2018 |author1=Thierry Dubois |author2=Guy Norris |author3=Victoria Moores |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>

In October 2018, analysts from [[Sanford C. Bernstein]], [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Canaccord Genuity]] were convinced Boeing would launch the project.<ref name=AvWeek17oct2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeings-new-midsize-airplane-will-happen-say-analysts |title= Boeing's New Midsize Airplane Will Happen, Say Analysts |date= Oct 17, 2018 |author= Michael Bruno |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> Boeing's Randy Tinseth stated an almost unanimous preference for better economics through weight savings rather than the heavier structure to carry widebody [[Unit load device|containers]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-quietly-plugs-away-at-nma-pending-2019-decis-453005/ |title= Boeing quietly plugs away at NMA pending 2019 decision |date= 26 Oct 2018 |author= Greg Waldron |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>

===2019===
By early 2019, Rolls-Royce was anticipating an addressable market for 4,000 to 5,000 middle-of-the-market aircraft over 20 years, agreeing with Boeing's figures, and pointed out that Boeing would not capture all of that market; it expected demand for the NMA to reach 2,000 to 3,000 aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2019/01/22/rolls-royces-sees-nma-addressable-market-as-4000-5000-same-as-boeing/ |title= Rolls-Royces sees NMA "addressable" market as 4,000–5,000, same as Boeing |date= Jan 22, 2019 |work= Leeham News}}</ref> Former Airbus sales executive John Leahy suggested that Boeing should create a new single-aisle aircraft to compete with the [[Airbus A321neo]] from 2030 instead of a small widebody.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2019/01/29/forget-the-nma-go-after-a321-say-ex-airbus-exec/ |title= Forget the NMA, go after A321–say ex-Airbus exec |date= Jan 29, 2019 |work= Leeham News}}</ref>

On January 30, 2019, then-Boeing CEO [[Dennis Muilenburg]] clarified that whether to ''offer'' the NMA for sale would be decided later in the year, before an ''authority to launch'' decision deferred until 2020, aligned with the end of 777X development and enabling the NMA to build on 777X work.<ref name=flightglobal20190130>{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=Boeing CEO: No NMA firm launch decision this year |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-ceo-no-nma-firm-launch-decision-this-year-455409/ |work=Flightglobal |date=30 January 2019}}</ref> The two-stage decision process is standard at Boeing and entry into service was still targeted for 2025, but the delay could cause 757 replacement opportunities to be missed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=Boeing buys time with 2020 NMA launch timeline |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-buys-time-with-2020-nma-launch-timeline-455456/ |work=Flightglobal |date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Boeing intended to leverage existing technologies such as [[composite materials|composites]] for the NMA. The program would overhaul [[supply chain]] practices and focus on more efficient production, support and maintenance that could also be applied to a future 737 replacement.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title= How the NMA might prepare Boeing for a 737 replacement |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-how-the-nma-might-prepare-boeing-for-a-737-455844/ |work=FlightGlobal |date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>

In February 2019, [[Rolls-Royce plc]] abandoned its engine proposal, leaving [[CFM International]] and [[Pratt & Whitney]] as sole competitors.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/rolls-royce-pulls-out-of-boeing-nma-engine-contest-456184/ |title= Rolls-Royce pulls out of Boeing NMA engine contest |date= 28 Feb 2019 |author= David Kaminski-Morrow |work=FlightGlobal}}</ref> A new development would not be mature enough as the [[Ultrafan]] program is too far away from Boeing's needs, but Rolls-Royce could be interested in a partnership with another manufacturer.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/rolls-royce-open-to-potential-partnership-on-nma-e-456208/ |title= Rolls-Royce 'open' to potential partnership on NMA engine: chief |date= 28 Feb 2019 |author= Michael Gubisch |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>

The chief executive of GE Aviation, for the second year in a row, expressed skepticism regarding the size of the market for the jet.<ref>{{cite news |title=United's A321XLR order shuts the lower end Mom to NMA |url=https://airinsight.com/uniteds-a321xlr-order-shuts-the-lower-end-mom-to-nma/ |access-date=3 February 2020 |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>

In June 2019, following the launch of the [[Airbus A321XLR]], Boeing was understood to be prioritizing the 275-seat variant, tentatively dubbed NMA-7X, ahead of the 225-seat NMA-6X which would compete more directly with the A321XLR. A formal ''authority to offer'' decision was still expected later in 2019.<ref name=AW_June2019>{{cite news |title=Boeing Pivots Towards Prioritizing Larger NMA Version First |url=https://aviationweek.com/paris-airshow-2019/boeing-pivots-towards-prioritizing-larger-nma-version-first |work=aviationweek.com |language=en }}{{Dead link|date=July 2024 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The two prospective engine suppliers were understood to be bidding on a sole-supplier basis, believing that market demand would not allow two competing engines to achieve a timely return on investment, whereas Air Lease Corporation's Steven Udvar-Házy felt that buyers should have a choice. Udvar-Házy also suggested that the NMA should be designed with future changes in mind, such as the possibility of single-pilot operation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=Udvar-Hazy foresees single-pilot evolution for NMA |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-udvar-hazy-foresees-single-pilot-evolution-fo-459137/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=18 June 2019}}</ref>

In July 2019, Boeing stated that its priority was the safe return to service of the [[Boeing 737 MAX groundings|grounded 737 MAX]], and that the decision to launch the NMA would depend partly on its confidence in the tools it intends to implement in order to improve development program performance.<ref name="flightglobal20190724">{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=Boeing warns of 737 production halt as grounding slams Q2 results |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-warns-of-737-production-halt-as-grounding-sla-459893/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=July 24, 2019}}</ref>

In September 2019, Airbus estimated the total addressable market for midsize aircraft to represent some 2,000 to 2,500 jets over the next 20 years, and noted that it would be "taking the early market" in this space with the A321XLR and high-density A321 configurations, and with the A330neo.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaminski-Morrow |first1=David |title=Airbus ventures estimate of NMA demand to 2038 |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/airbus-ventures-estimate-of-nma-demand-to-2038-460933/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=September 18, 2019 |access-date=}}</ref>

{{Multiple image
| image1            = N845MH Boeing 767-400 Delta (14728540733).jpg
| caption1          = The 767-400 is the largest and currently the latest commercial version of the existing [[Boeing 767|767 series]].
| image2            = Domodedovo IMG 1775 (6869381879).jpg
| direction         = vertical
| caption2          = A new-generation [[General Electric GEnx]] engine
| header            = Considered 767-XF concept
}}

By October, Boeing was studying a re-engined 767-XF for around 2025, based on the [[767-400ER]] with an extended landing gear to accommodate [[General Electric GEnx]] turbofans.<!--ref name=Flight10oct2019-->
The cargo market was the main target, but a passenger version could be a less expensive alternative to the proposed NMA.<ref name=Flight10oct2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/boeing-examines-genx-powered-767-x-for-cargo-and-pa-461386/ |title= Boeing examines GEnx-powered 767-X for cargo and passenger roles |date= 10 Oct 2019 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> Some airlines and lessors touted as NMA customers had been pushing Boeing to focus instead on a narrow-body aircraft, dubbed the Future Small Airplane (FSA), to replace the 737 MAX, and cast doubt on whether the NMA would be launched.<ref name="aircurrent-20191028">{{cite news |title=Boeing's NMA in doubt as airlines take fresh look at 737 Max & 757 replacement |url=https://theaircurrent.com/aircraft-development/boeings-nma-in-doubt-as-airlines-take-fresh-look-at-737-max-757-replacement/ |work=The Air Current |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>

In December, United Airlines placed an order for 50 A321XLRs to replace its aging fleet of 757s,<ref name="flight-20191204">{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=United places firm order for 50 A321XLRs |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/united-places-firm-order-for-50-a321xlrs-462668/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> its first narrow-body Airbus order since 2006,<!-- <ref name="flight-20191205" /> --> but stated that this did not rule out consideration of the NMA in the future. Analysts Richard Aboulafia and Rob Morris both believed that, although it would be a strong contender to replace the 767, the chances of a wide-body NMA being launched were diminishing in favour of a narrow-body aircraft that would compete more directly with the A321XLR.<ref name="flight-20191205">{{cite news |last1=Goldstein |first1=Steve |title=ANALYSIS: United's Airbus order spawns visions of a different NMA |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-uniteds-airbus-order-spawns-visions-of-a-462685/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>

=== 2020 ===
On 22 January 2020, Boeing's new chief executive [[David Calhoun]] announced a clean sheet reevaluation of the project, as the company focused on existing products and the market shifted away after Airbus launched the popular A321XLR in 2019.<!--ref name=Flight23jan2020--> Boeing also noted its realization, following the 737 MAX crashes, that any new design must focus on the flight control system and how pilots interact with the aircraft.<ref name=Flight23jan2020>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/air-transport/boeing-to-take-another-clean-sheet-to-nma-with-focus-on-pilots/136296.article |title= Boeing to take another 'clean sheet' to NMA with focus on pilots |author= Jon Hemmerdinger |date= 23 January 2020 |work= flightglobal}}</ref>

[[File:Dreamliner render 787-3.JPG|thumb|The 787-3 is an abandoned variant of the [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787 Dreamliner family]], being equivalently sized to a 787-8 but was adjusted for shorter flights.]]

Boeing ordered a new study to assess the future market and the kind of aircraft that could meet that market, effectively shelving its current plan.<!--ref name=Reuters23jan2020--> Boeing was losing market share to the 200 to 240-seat Airbus A321 in particular, which targets a similar segment of the market to the NMA.<!--ref name=Reuters23jan2020--> The delay to the NMA launch had already put a key part of the target market at risk for Boeing, particularly after Airbus won contracts with two major U.S. airlines.<!--ref name=Reuters23jan2020--> Analysts<!-- not named in reference --> also questioned if Boeing had the appetite for the expense of the NMA project as it faced "costs equivalent to a new program to repair the MAX crisis" and delays on the 777X program.<ref name=Reuters23jan2020>{{cite news |last1=Hepher |first1=Tim |last2=Rucinski |first2=Tracy |title=Boeing's new CEO orders rethink on key jetliner project |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-boeing-737max-nma/boeings-new-ceo-orders-rethink-on-key-jetliner-project-idUSKBN1ZL2RM |work=Reuters |date=23 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> One option postulated for Boeing would be to revive the [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner#787-3|787-3]], a 787 variant optimized for short-haul use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolfsteller |first1=Pilar |title=Analyst: Boeing's previously scrapped 787-3 could be reborn as the NMA |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/airframers/analyst-boeings-previously-scrapped-787-3-could-be-reborn-as-the-nma/136589.article |work=Flight Global |date=February 7, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>

=== 2021 ===
By early 2021, Boeing was studying a shorter -5X variant to compete with the [[Airbus A321XLR]] as a 757-200/300 successor with a range of {{cvt|5,000|nmi|km}}.<ref name=AvWeek4feb2021/>
A smaller 225-seat variant of the previous NMA twin-aisle design with composite wings and fuselage, it would reuse existing structures, systems and engine technology to target production costs comparable to single-aisle aircraft.<ref name=AvWeek4feb2021/> It would be powered by derated versions of the higher-bypass ratio {{cvt|50,000|lbf|kN}} engines proposed by [[CFM International]] and by [[Pratt & Whitney]], while [[Rolls-Royce plc]] may be able to reconsider its withdrawal from bidding.<ref name=AvWeek4feb2021/> Boeing could spend $2–3 billion a year for the development, up to $25 billion, as a potential go-ahead in 2022 or 2023 could lead to a late 2020s service entry.<ref name=AvWeek4feb2021>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/aerospace/manufacturing-supply-chain/boeing-moves-forward-airbus-a321xlr-competitor-plan |title= Boeing Moves Forward With Airbus A321XLR-Competitor Plan |author= Guy Norris |date= February 4, 2021 |work= Aviation Week}}</ref>

Analysts estimate that narrow-body aircraft will account for around 70% of sales by 2025, and believe a clean-sheet NMA to be essential for Boeing to avoid losing market share to Airbus, and to the A321neo in particular.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolfsteller |first1=Pilar |title=Why Boeing needs to work quickly on NMA decision |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/aerospace/why-boeing-needs-to-work-quickly-on-nma-decision/142359.article |work=Flight Global |date=February 10, 2021}}</ref> Airbus could attain a 60% overall market share, yet analysts believe Boeing is unlikely to launch a new mid-market aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hemmerdinger |first1=Jon |title=Analysts urge Boeing: launch a mid-market jet |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/airframers/analysts-urge-boeing-launch-a-mid-market-jet/142379.article |work=Flight Global |date=February 10, 2021}}</ref>

=== 2022 ===
In June 2022, Boeing indicated that it would not pursue development of the NMA for "at least a couple of years", until significant progress has been made on the next generation of engines and until new digital development tools are sufficiently mature.<ref name="seattletimes20220603">{{cite news |last1=Johnsson |first1=Julie |title=Boeing CEO sees at least 2-year wait on designing new jetliner |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-ceo-sees-at-least-2-year-wait-on-designing-new-jetliner/ |work=The Seattle Times |agency=Bloomberg |date=3 June 2022}}</ref>
[[File:Boeing 757-2Q8, TACV Cabo Verde Airlines JP485148.jpg|thumb|There is currently no modern engine solution available to directly replace the {{Convert|200|kN|lbf}}-class [[Pratt & Whitney PW2000|PW2000]] (pictured) and [[Rolls-Royce RB211|RB211]] that power the [[Boeing 757|757]].]]

== Engines ==
The engine selection process is reminiscent of the competition to power the [[777-200LR]]/[[777-300ER|300ER]] at the end of the 1990s, which shaped the turbofan market for the subsequent years. Rolls-Royce proposed the [[Rolls-Royce Trent#Trent 8104|Trent 8104]] growth demonstrator, Pratt & Whitney proposed a scaled-up [[PW6000]] (wanting to limit the competition to two suppliers), while GE won exclusivity with the [[GE90]]-115B performance and [[GECAS]] 777 orders.<!--<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>--> Rolls-Royce obtained the same exclusivity for the [[Airbus A350|A350]] and later the [[Airbus A330neo|A330neo]], pushing P&W out of the widebody engine market and precipitating its narrowbody comeback with the [[PW1000G]].<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>

[[File:Airbus A321-251NX (TC-RDK), Istanbul SAW (TR) -- 2024 -- 0139.jpg|thumb|The engines on the new [[Airbus A321neo]] - including A321XLR and being currently the largest [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrowbody aircraft]] in production - are certified at less than {{Convert|150|kN|lbf}}. That being said, the [[Airbus A321|A321]] is a much smaller and lighter platform than the [[Boeing 757|757-200]], being intended for shorter-ranged operations.]]
[[File:Boeing 747-8F GENx engines and main landing gear.jpg|thumb|The GENx-2B - exclusively powering the [[Boeing 747-8]] - is cited as a feasible available option to re-engine and modernize the existing [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767 platform]]. However, with a certified thrust of {{Convert|300|kN|lbf}}, it is significantly overpowered for virtually all [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrowbody]] NMA concepts.]]
The {{cvt|45,000|lbf|kN}} thrust was typical of the 1960s' first generation of high-bypass-ratio turbofans: the [[GE CF6]] for [[Douglas DC-10]], the Rolls [[RB211]] for [[Lockheed Tristar]], and the [[Pratt & Whitney JT9D]] for [[Boeing 747]]. This market was quickly left behind as aircraft and their power requirements grew, leaving the RB211 for [[Boeing 757]] (until 2005), or the Pratt [[PW2000]] for [[Boeing C-17]]. Newer technology enabled 10:1 or more [[bypass ratio]]s and [[overall pressure ratio]]s of at least 50:1 at top of climb.<!--<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>--> This level of thrust is above modern [[CFM LEAP]] or Pratt [[Pratt & Whitney PW1000G|PW1000G]] single-aisle engines, but well below [[Rolls-Royce Trent]] or [[GEnx]] widebody ones.<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>

It falls below the {{cvt|50,000|lbf|kN}} limit for [[CFM International]], and thus a scaled-down [[GE9X]] core could fit a new low-pressure system.<!--<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>--> Pratt could reach it by growing from the {{cvt|33,000|lbf|kN}} PW1133G for the [[Airbus A321neo|A321neo]].<!--<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>--> Rolls could propose its [[Ultrafan|UltraFan]] development, a [[geared turbofan]] based its new Advance core, but it is primarily focused on its larger, {{cvt|100,000|lbf|kN}} engine.<!--<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107/>--> The GTF cost more than $10 billion to develop, and RR was facing financial difficulties which could be accelerated by being left out of the EU [[Clean Sky]] initiative as a result of [[Brexit]]. Both could join together, but have historically been moving in the opposite direction, as Rolls sold its 32.5% stake in [[International Aero Engines]] to Pratt parent [[United Technologies]] in 2011, essentially selling the ghost of the geared [[IAE SuperFan]] proposed for the [[Airbus A340|A340]] (supplanted in 1987 by the [[CFM56]]).<ref name=AvWeek2jun2107>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/technology/boeing-s-nma-poses-propulsion-puzzle-engine-makers |title= Boeing's NMA Poses Propulsion Puzzle For Engine Makers |date= June 2, 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>

CFM International has also considered geared turbofan architecture for the prospective aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://atwonline.com/paris-air-show-2017/cfm-hints-possible-geared-fan-engine-middle-market-aircraft |title= CFM hints at possible geared fan engine for middle of market aircraft |date= June 21, 2017 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week Network}}</ref> GE has expressed that it does not believe the market is large enough for all three suppliers and will not enter a three-way race which would not justify the investment needed–as was the case for the [[Airbus A330#Engines|A330's engines]]–leaving Boeing's NMA with two suppliers at most.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-19/ge-tells-boeing-it-won-t-share-797-engines-with-two-arch-rivals |title= GE Tells Boeing It Won't Join Three-Way Race on 797 Plane Engine |author= Christopher Jasper, Benjamin D Katz and Julie Johnsson |date= 19 June 2017 |work= Bloomberg}}</ref>

Boeing has not yet decided whether it will use a single engine type: CFM considers an all-new direct-drive engine, and Rolls-Royce proposes its Advance direct-drive engine before 2025 and its UltraFan geared design after, scalable from {{cvt|25,000|to|110,000|lbf|kN}}.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/singapore-boeing-studying-three-different-nma-en-445673/ |title= Boeing studying three 'different' NMA engine designs |date= 7 Feb 2018 |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> As a new engine development costs [[United States dollar|US$]]2.5 to $3 billion, GE has to evaluate its [[Market opportunity|market opportunities]], preferring a single-source for a low-volume airplane while Airbus would potentially need such an engine.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/singapore-ge-outlines-thinking-around-nma-engine-b-445719/ |title= GE outlines thinking around NMA engine business case |date= 8 Feb 2018 |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> GE Aviation's offer would be through CFM, with the LEAP as the baseline for a bigger engine, half a generation further, with advanced but mature enough technology.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://leehamnews.com/2018/03/22/ge-cfm-in-lockstep-with-boeing-on-nma/ |title= GE/CFM in "lockstep" with Boeing on NMA |date= March 22, 2018 |work= Leeham News}}</ref>

Boeing issued a [[request for proposals]] (RFP) with a June 27, 2018 deadline for a {{cvt|45,000|lbf|kN}} engine with a [[thrust specific fuel consumption]] (TSFC) 25% lower than the 757's engines.<ref name=Ostrower26jun2018>{{cite news |url= https://preview.theaircurrent.com |date= June 26, 2018 |title= Engine trio has due date for Boeing NMA proposals |author= Jon Ostrower |work= The Air Current |access-date= October 19, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180628124825/https://preview.theaircurrent.com/ |archive-date= June 28, 2018 |url-status= dead}}</ref> At least two engine-makers want exclusivity for the $2 billion program cost.<!--<ref name=AvWeek20jul2018>--> Even if its thrust crept to {{cvt|52,000|lbf|kN}}, GE and Safran will bid through their CFM joint venture with a 3D-woven-[[resin transfer molding]] fan like the Leap instead of a GEnx/GE9X-type carbon-fiber composite.<ref name=AvWeek20jul2018>{{cite news |title=Airbus Moves Ahead With A321XLR Definition |url=http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/airbus-moves-ahead-a321xlr-definition |author1=Jens Flottau |author2=Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology |date=20 July 2018}}</ref>

In 2025, the [[United States Air Force]] announced that it looks for new generation turbofans in the {{cvt|35,000-52,000|lbf|kN}} sector, which may encourage developments of new engines in this neglected sector and eventually assist Boeing's NMA ambitions.<ref>{{Cite web |title=U.S. Air Force Office Pitches Engine Investment For Mid-Market Airliner {{!}} Aviation Week Network |url=https://aviationweek.com/defense/aircraft-propulsion/us-air-force-office-pitches-engine-investment-mid-market-airliner |url-access=subscription |access-date=2025-07-13 |website=aviationweek.com}}</ref>

